7) intensify collection efforts by issuing demand letters to accountable officers to liquidate or settle their remaining cash advances. This can be used as a basis to implement administrative proceedings/sanctions to particular accountable officers who failed to liquidate their cash advances despite successive issuance of demand letters;
8) exhaust all remedies to demand the liquidation of the cash advance from the retired employee and proceed with the procedures as provided under COA Circular No. 2016-005 to request for write-off of the account, as deemed applicable;
9) require all concerned accountable officers to submit immediately the liquidation reports of the remaining unliquidated cash advances and submit the same reports to the audit team for verification and to avoid the issuance of a Notice of Suspension or Disallowance; and
10) enforce strictly the liquidation of the cash advances within the prescribed period, in accordance with COA Circular No. 97-002, Section 89 of PD 1445, and COA Circular No. 2012-001 to prevent the further accumulation of the unliquidated cash advances.

11.expedite the disposal of unserviceable properties in accordance with the guidelines/policies stipulated in Sec. 79 of PD 1445 and COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1 to deter further deterioration of such assets;
12. initiate the transfer of ownership of PPE items that are already in possession of and controlled by end-users other than the Municipality and comply with the necessary documentary requirements;
13. conduct an investigation on properties that are no longer physically existing and prepare the necessary documentation to facilitate their proper disposition, in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006;
