15. effect the necessary journal entries to derecognize non-existing/missing PPE items from the books, provided that all the supporting documents required under COA Circular No. 2020-006 are duly complied with;
16. ensure derecognition of PPE items from the books of account of the Municipality once the transfer of ownership of other PPE items has been completed, in compliance with IPSAS 17;
17. ensure that the proper accounting and reporting procedures for all acquisition/issuance/transfer/disposal of government assets are pursuant to the existing manuals and other relevant laws, rules and regulations after the completion of the one-time cleansing; and
18. undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and that the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the Property Unit and the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Unit are reconciled.

20.) direct the concerned offices to coordinate closely with the respective source agencies to obtain all necessary supporting documents, including but not limited to Memoranda of Agreement (MOAs), Trust Agreements (TAs), and Fund Utilization Reports (FURs), to establish the legal foundation, terms, and conditions governing the receipt and intended use of the transferred funds;
21.) in the absence of the required documentation, conduct a comprehensive assessment of the status of the projects or programs funded by these transfers to ascertain whether the funds were utilized in accordance with their intended purposes;
22.) after the assessment, engage the source agencies to determine the appropriate disposition of any unexpended balances. If return is required, direct the Municipal Treasurer to return/remit to the Source Agencies such remaining balance. Otherwise, file a request to the Source Agencies for the authority to transfer the said unexpended balances to the General Fund, in accordance with COA Circular No. 2012-001;
23.) furnish the audit team with a copy of the source documents (MOA, TA, or MOU) of the fund transfers for review and evaluation; and
24.) improve internal controls by implementing clear and strict procedures for documenting, monitoring, and reporting fund transfers. This will ensure compliance with financial standards, protect public funds, and prevent similar issues from recurring.

